tweet: If the test is implemented with a leadership mentality change, I‚Äôm absolutely here for it. I‚Äôd love to know what others think on this....

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: The culture surrounding PT will need to change for it to have the desired impact of the force. We won‚Äôt PT as a unit any larger than a fire team anymore and that‚Äôs ok. We won‚Äôt waste Soldier‚Äôs time with exercises that aren‚Äôt helping them achieve their goals.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: Bc Training for an additional 3 months on their own schedule will allow them to at least pass the test, especially if they are not concerned about also passing height and weight. Strength is what counts.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: New moms know how to sacrifice to meet a goal.  Most women with uncomplicated deliveries can return to physical activity after 6 weeks, and can begin weighted abdominal exercises (like the hanging leg raise) after 3 months.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: For the ACFT to be successful, especially in terms of implementation with Postpartum women or those recovery from injury, we need to  implement this goal based fitness approach.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: I could have managed my own time, lifted weights, pumped breast milk for longer because I wasn‚Äôt worried about dropping weight to make tape. Not adding these additional arbitrary stresses to new moms will allow them to be better leaders and parents.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: If after I had my daughter six years ago as a 1LT I didn‚Äôt have to drop her off at daycare at 6 am to be at postpartum PT to walk around a track for an hour, I would have recovered and returned to duty much quicker.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet:
Postpartum Moms

If implemented, individualized fitness will be the greatest thing ever to happen to a postpartum female Soldier.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: so they will just not do as well in some events. BMI should not be a constraining factor on their athletic performance.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: Soldiers will be working on different aspects of the test at different times, based on their individual goals, meaning they might be carb cycling (also know as gaining weight to gain muscle) or leaning out for goals outside of the ACFT (marathons, triathlon, bodybuilding)

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet:
BMI is antiqued and used outside of its intended purpose. I‚Äôm sure you‚Äôve seen the studies.
For post-partum moms this is honestly more of a concern that actually meeting the test standards. It shouldn‚Äôt be that way. The BMI index has no place in the Army of the future.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: If the standard is survivability and lethality in combat and that means a Soldier is able to complete the ACFT tasks to standard, then there should be no other standard.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet:
No more height and weight

The transition to goal based fitness means we can do away with arbitrary measures like BMI or height and weight as indicators of combat effectiveness.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: Soldiers need to think and plan for themselves, knowing they have a standard to meet to keep their job and train as such. Leaders must ‚Äúprotect the time‚Äù for PT but should not dictate what training looks like.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet: If the future of warfare, according to General Brown, ( https://youtu.be/qOTYgcdNrXE¬†) is that we are engaged in a four dimensional chess match where the pieces think for themselves, we no longer have time to do the bend and reach in formation.

name: Stephanie Worth
tweet:
Goal Based Approach

I think the ACFT is an amazing opportunity for the Army to move away from a one size fits all approach to fitness and create goal oriented training that becomes an individual responsibility.
